text: I just don't know how to feel about this... The way it's shot feels so different from the previous 7, the use of an upbeat song in the latter half of the trailer gives off the vibe that they are going for more of a fun movie (like Final Destination) as opposed to the super serious dark stuff that the previous movies had (sans saw 3d).  It doesn't feel like SAW.  It feels like... a knockoff of SAW, not a true SAW.  If it's any consolation, it does look better than saw 3d.  But definitely looks to be its own kind of vibe and universe as opposed to being a dark and twisted affair like the first six.    I'm what you would call a superfan of the series, but I disowned saw 3d since it is a piece of shit in every way, and bordering on offensive to the fans that got the series to that point.  It was just awful, especially disappointing after the stellar SAW VI.    JigSAW is not looking great, though.  I especially hate that line about "Well that's not creepy."  Can we not add one-liner quips into the series?  This isn't a Marvel or Star Wars movie.  SAW doesn't need quips and humor.  It needs a stellar storyline that some people will consider convoluted and contrived, traps that have deep metaphorical meaning, amazing twists that make you rethink the entire film, and incredible Charlie Clouser music to round it all out.  Based on this trailer, I feel like only a couple of those criteria will be ticked off the list.  It honestly feels like a direct-to-DVD movie.  Long story short, coming from a SAW superfan, I will of course give this movie a chance, it does look better than saw 3d, but this does not look like the incredible return to form that I think a lot of us were hoping for.  This definitely won't be topping SAW VI as my favorite, that's for sure.

text: Saw was a game changing film for the Horror Genre, it ushered in the age of the Torture Porn film or New Wave Extremity as the French say. It made James Wan and Leigh Whannell household names in Hollywood. A slew of horror flicks afterwards as well as the Insidious and Conjuring franchises. But as the series went on, it's just became too ridiculous to believe and became bogged down in its own mythos. By the end of the series, everybody involved in the murders, those investigating them and those affected by them are dead.¬† Dr. Lawrence Gordon seems to be the sole survivor with him locking Det. Hoffman in the Room to die. But in Saw unless we see you die, can you really be sure? The positive thing about this film it does seem to be returning to the essentials of the first film, narrower focus and tighter storytelling. The story will be split between the Cops investigating the murders and the new group of victims in the Jigsaw ordeal. It will be interesting who has taken up John Kramer's mantle of Jigsaw. Also more Tobin Bell is always appreciate, hopefully this is a step back in the right direction for these films.
